      <title>Why Chinese Cops Now Patrol the Streets of Rome, Milan</title>
      <pubDate>Thu, 12 May 2016 09:37:47 GMT</pubDate>
      <link>http://www.nbcnews.com/news/china/chinese-police-patrol-italians-rome-milan-tourist-sites-n572596</link>
      <dc:creator>Claudio Lavanga</dc:creator>
      <description>Chinese police are patrolling the streets of Rome and Milan this month as part of an experimental police exchange program between the two countries.</description>
      <media:content url="http://media1.s-nbcnews.com/i/newscms/2016_19/1533946/160512-world-italy-chinese-police-rome-350a_1ec7e77d7ab7338d9fa2adb1b63797be.jpg" medium="image" height="2448" width="3264">
        <media:credit>Claudio Lavanga</media:credit>
        <media:text type="plain"></media:text>
        <media:description type="plain">Chinese tourists take a selfie with a Chinese police officer in Rome who is there as part of an program with Italian law enforcement.</media:description>
      </media:content>
      <media:content url="http://media3.s-nbcnews.com/i/newscms/2016_19/1533951/160512-world-italy-chinese-police-rome-front-350a_bce5bf643fe2f7e763ba83d34c348362.jpg" medium="image" height="2448" width="3264">
        <media:credit>Claudio Lavanga</media:credit>
        <media:text type="plain">Image: Bo Pang and Italian police officer</media:text>
        <media:description type="plain">Chinese police officer Bo Pang is among those on patrol in Rome and Milan this month alongside Italian counterparts.</media:description>
      </media:content>
      <media:content url="http://media1.s-nbcnews.com/i/newscms/2016_19/1533946/160512-world-italy-chinese-police-rome-350a_1ec7e77d7ab7338d9fa2adb1b63797be.jpg" medium="image" height="2448" width="3264">
        <media:credit>Claudio Lavanga</media:credit>
        <media:text type="plain"></media:text>
        <media:description type="plain">Chinese tourists take a selfie with Pang Bo in Rome.</media:description>
      </media:content>
    </item>

      <description>French prosecutors say $2 million tied to Tokyo's bid for the 2020 Olympics was paid to an account linked to the son of a disgraced athletics chief.</description>

        <media:text type="plain">Image: FILES-OLY2020-JAPAN-FRANCE-CORRUPTION</media:text>
        <media:description type="plain">Papa Massata Diack is seen in this 2015 file photo. French investigators suspect he may have been paid $2M tied to the Tokyo 2020 Olympic games winning bid.</media:description>
      </media:content>
      <media:content url="http://media2.s-nbcnews.com/i/newscms/2016_19/1534531/160512-world-france-probe-tokyo-2020-diack-1125a-jpg-1118_e49d3cec94d6fd674bf3904b26f44b9f.jpg" medium="image" height="3480" width="2376">

        <media:text type="plain">Image: FILES-OLY2020-JAPAN-FRANCE-CORRUPTION</media:text>

      <title>Teen's Streamed Suicide on Periscope Leads to Inquiry</title>
      <pubDate>Thu, 12 May 2016 14:11:00 GMT</pubDate>
      <link>http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/french-teen-s-streamed-suicide-periscope-leads-inquiry-n572786</link>
      <dc:creator>Associated Press</dc:creator>
      <description>French authorities have opened an investigation after a teenager allegedly live-streamed video of her suicide on the popular app Periscope.</description>
      <media:content url="http://media2.s-nbcnews.com/i/newscms/2016_19/1534341/160512-egly-station-mdl_b50f365e17bf84642507cbfa0e6a2f61.jpg" medium="image" height="3456" width="5184">
        <media:credit>Christophe Ena</media:credit>
        <media:text type="plain"></media:text>
        <media:description type="plain">A train starts at the Egly station, south of Paris, on May 11, 2016. French authorities opened an investigation Wednesday after a teenage woman allegedly live-streamed video of her suicide on the popular app Periscope. The local prosecutor said the young woman threw herself under a commuter train in the suburban Egly station, south of Paris.</media:description>
      </media:content>
    </item>

      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/brazil-senate-votes-impeach-president-dilma-rousseff-n572606</guid>
      <title>Brazil's President Blasts Impeachment Vote as 'a Coup'</title>
      <pubDate>Thu, 12 May 2016 12:57:25 GMT</pubDate>
      <link>http://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/brazil-senate-votes-impeach-president-dilma-rousseff-n572606</link>
      <dc:creator>Alastair Jamieson and Emmanuelle Saliba and The Associated Press</dc:creator>
      <description>Brazil's Senate voted to impeach President Dilma Rousseff early Thursday amid the worst economic crisis there since the 1930s.</description>
      <media:content url="http://media2.s-nbcnews.com/i/newscms/2016_19/1533976/160512-world-brazil-dilma-530a-jpg-0526_e700da51a6d6091c9c2dbafaf59c0bba.jpg" medium="image" height="1968" width="3000">
        <media:credit>Mario Tama</media:credit>
        <media:text type="plain">Image: Embattled Brazilian President Dilma Rousseff Addresses Crowd In Brasilia</media:text>
        <media:description type="plain">Embattled Brazilian President Dilma Rousseff waves as she enters to speak at a conference on Tuesday.</media:description>
      </media:content>
      <media:content url="http://media2.s-nbcnews.com/i/newscms/2016_19/1533976/160512-world-brazil-dilma-530a-jpg-0526_e700da51a6d6091c9c2dbafaf59c0bba.jpg" medium="image" height="1968" width="3000">
        <media:credit>Mario Tama</media:credit>
        <media:text type="plain">Image: Dilma Rousseff</media:text>
        <media:description type="plain">Brazilian President Dilma Rousseff waves as she attended a conference on Tuesday.</media:description>
      </media:content>
      <media:content url="http://media4.s-nbcnews.com/i/newscms/2016_19/1533971/160512-world-brazil-senate-vote-530a-jpg-0524_b8b7ae55a77159342516214b9e6f1c58.jpg" medium="image" height="3372" width="5058">
        <media:credit>Igo Estrela</media:credit>
        <media:text type="plain">Image: Senate In Brazil Votes On Impeachment Of President Dilma Rousseff</media:text>
